---
/**
 * The verification page: exactly what the build proves, per THING, and what
 * rests on citation (ADR-0007). This page is the project's honesty contract —
 * AI-authored content, programmatic gates, no human review, stated plainly.
 */
import { getCollection } from "astro:content";
import katex from "katex";
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import { withBase } from "../lib/url";

const compiled = (await getCollection("compiled"))
  .map((c) => c.data)
  .sort((a, b) => a.title.localeCompare(b.title));

const tex = (s: string) => katex.renderToString(s, { displayMode: false, throwOnError: true });

const rows = compiled.map((a) => {
  const identities = a.derivation.filter((d) => d.check === "identity").length;
  const modeling = a.derivation.filter((d) => d.check === "definition");
  const envelopes = a.relations.flatMap((r) =>
    r.validity.map((v) => ({ severity: v.severity, message: v.message })),
  );
  const samples = a.configurations.reduce((n, c) => n + c.samples.length, 0);
  const guards = a.configurations.reduce((n, c) => n + c.guards.length, 0);
  const sourceById = new Map(a.sources.map((s) => [s.id, s]));
  return { a, identities, modeling, envelopes, samples, guards, sourceById };
});

const totals = {
  things: rows.length,
  relations: rows.reduce((n, r) => n + r.a.relations.length, 0),
  identities: rows.reduce((n, r) => n + r.identities, 0),
  modeling: rows.reduce((n, r) => n + r.modeling.length, 0),
  samples: rows.reduce((n, r) => n + r.samples, 0),
};
---

<Base
  title="Verification"
  description="What the build proves, per THING, and what rests on citation. AI-authored; no human review."
>
  <article>
    <h1>What is verified here — and what isn't</h1>

    <p>
      This site is <strong>built end to end by an AI</strong> (Anthropic's Claude) operating
      documentation and verification systems designed by the project owner.
      <strong>No human reviews the content.</strong> What stands between you and a wrong number is
      the machinery on this page — stated plainly so you can judge it. Everything here is
      educational material, <a href={withBase("about/")}>not for design use</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>What the build proves, every time</h2>
    <p class="citation">
      A page cannot deploy unless every one of these gates passes; a failure names the THING, the
      relation, and the step.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Dimensional homogeneity</strong> — every relation's terms carry identical SI
        dimension 7-vectors; transcendental functions take dimensionless arguments only. Dimension
        alone is not enough, so every variable also carries a <em>quantity kind</em>: a beam's shear
        flow, a distributed load, and a spring rate are all newtons per metre and share the identical
        dimension vector, yet the type system forbids chaining one into another because their kinds
        (<code>shear_flow</code>, <code>line_load</code>, <code>stiffness</code>) differ — same units,
        three meanings, kept apart on purpose.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Degree-of-freedom arithmetic</strong> — each configuration's knob count equals
        variables minus independent relations, with independence established by Jacobian rank
        <em>on the solution manifold</em>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Solution verification</strong> — every authored closed form is substituted back
        into <em>every</em> relation and must vanish: a tiered symbolic prover, then ≥30
        high-precision (50-digit) numeric samples across the declared domain, per solution branch.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Bracketed numeric targets (solve1d)</strong> — a value with no closed form (the
        eccentric column's load at first yield) is solved live in your browser by bracketed
        root-finding, never symbol-blind solving. The build proves, at every verification
        sample: the authored bracket really brackets (a residual sign change), contains exactly
        one root, and the 60-digit bisection root satisfies <em>every</em> relation — and those
        roots ship as reference values, so the browser's root-finder is checked against them on
        each build.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Tabulated data (tables)</strong> — a value published as a cited table rather than
        a formula (the Lewis gear-tooth form factor) is looked up in your browser, and the build
        proves, at every verification sample: the emitted lookup returns each published row
        <em>bit-exactly</em>, interpolates linearly between rows (pinned against 50-digit mpmath in
        the parity oracle), and <em>refuses</em> outside the tabulated domain — scoped to that
        column and its dependents, carrying the table's citation. No clamp, no extrapolation.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Derivation identities</strong> — every derivation line not badged as a modeling
        step is proven to follow from the verified solutions by computer algebra.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Independent physics cross-checks</strong> — the test pipeline re-derives cited
        results from first principles where possible (integrating stress distributions, re-solving
        boundary-value problems from equilibrium + compatibility, taking limiting cases), plus a
        hand-checkable numeric golden per THING.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Display integrity</strong> — generated JavaScript is checked against
        SymPy-computed reference values (parity oracle); every display unit must resolve in the
        conversion table; all LaTeX must render; envelope violations surface as banners and
        refused values, never silent numbers. Where two models share a page (Euler and Johnson
        on the column), each model's invalid region refuses <em>its own readouts by name</em>
        while the governing model's numbers stand — a scoped refusal, never a silent swap.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>End-to-end goldens</strong> — a browser test suite checks hand-derived numbers,
        material-cascade behavior, and refusal states against the built site, plus an
        accessibility smoke test.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What the machine cannot prove</h2>
    <p>
      Computer algebra proves <em>consequence</em>, not <em>physics</em>. Each THING's derivation
      begins from steps where physics enters by citation — a constitutive law, a boundary
      condition, a classical field solution. Those are badged
      <span class="step-definition">modeling step</span> on every page, and they are the complete
      list of places where this site asks you to trust a book instead of a proof. Citations are
      pinned against accessible documents where possible, and the pinning method is recorded
      below; a citation that says <em>topic-level</em> was not pinned to a section. Corrections
      land in the <a href={withBase("about/#errata")}>errata log</a> — dated, never silent.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Tabulated numbers are cited data, not proof.</strong> When a THING reads a value from
      a published table — the Lewis form factor <em>Y</em> for a gear tooth, from Shigley Table 14-2
      — the build proves the <em>machinery</em> (the lookup hits every published point exactly,
      interpolates linearly between them, and refuses outside the range), but the tabulated numbers
      themselves come from a book, and that interpolating between rows is legitimate is a cited
      modeling choice. <em>Y</em> in particular is laid out graphically from the tooth profile and
      cannot practically be re-derived from first principles, so its cross-check is a second
      published table, not a computation — while the gear pair's kinematics and force path
      <em>are</em> re-derived from equilibrium in the test pipeline.
    </p>

    <p class="citation">
      Catalog totals: {totals.things} THINGs · {totals.relations} relations (each cited) ·
      {totals.identities} derivation identities machine-proven · {totals.modeling} modeling steps
      (the audit surface) · {totals.samples} parity samples.
    </p>

    {
      rows.map(({ a, identities, modeling, envelopes, samples, guards, sourceById }) => (
        <section class="relation-block">
          <h3>
            <a href={withBase(`things/${a.thing}/`)}>{a.title}</a>
          </h3>
          <p class="citation">
            {a.relations.length} relations · {identities} identities proven ·{" "}
            {`${modeling.length} modeling step${modeling.length === 1 ? "" : "s"}`} ·{" "}
            {`${envelopes.length} validity envelope${envelopes.length === 1 ? "" : "s"}`} ·{" "}
            {`${guards} domain guard${guards === 1 ? "" : "s"}`} · {samples} parity samples
          </p>
          {modeling.length ? (
            <div>
              <p>
                <strong>Where physics enters</strong> (everything else on that page follows by
                machine-proven algebra):
              </p>
              <ul>
                {modeling.map((m) => (
                  <li>
                    <Fragment set:html={tex(m.latex)} /> — <em>{m.rule}</em>
                  </li>
                ))}
              </ul>
            </div>
          ) : (
            <p>
              No modeling steps: this THING's derivation is identities all the way down (its
              physics enters through the relations' cited assumptions instead).
            </p>
          )}
          <p>
            <strong>Sources & how they were checked:</strong>
          </p>
          <ul>
            {a.sources.map((s) => (
              <li class="citation">
                {s.citation}
                {s.verification ? (
                  <>
                    {" "}
                    — <strong>checked:</strong> {s.verification}
                  </>
                ) : (
                  <>
                    {" "}
                    — <strong>checked:</strong> not section-pinned; cited from general knowledge of
                    the text.
                  </>
                )}
              </li>
            ))}
          </ul>
        </section>
      ))
    }

    <p>
      Material property values carry their own per-value provenance (source, locator, original
      units, statistical basis) on the <a href={withBase("materials/")}>materials page</a>, under
      the rules in the repository's <code>docs/data-provenance.md</code>.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
